"Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Murdac","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Irish, Scottish:  see  Murdoch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Murdoch","meanings":["Scottish: from an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal names <i>Muireadhach</i> ‘mariner’, <i>Murchadh</i> ‘sea-warrior’, and <i>Muircheartach</i> ‘sea-ruler’, the first element in each being <i>muir</i> ‘sea’. The personal name was introduced into Yorkshire and Normandy by Norsemen from Ireland as early as the 10th century. The surname in post-Conquest medieval England usually belongs to Norman families."]}]},{"name":"Beatrice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and French form of   Beatrix  , which was quite popular in England during the Middle Ages, and strongly revived in the 19th century. It is most famous as the name of Dante's beloved, and is borne by the elder (  b. 1988 ) of the Duke of York's daughters."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":21,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Beatrice de Murdac was born about 1194, in Broughton, Oxfordshire, England, her father, Ralph de Murdac, was 49 and her mother, Eva Grey, was 31. She married Robert de Mauduit II in 1220, in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1221, at the age of 28."},"et":{"about 1194–1221":"umbes 1194–1221","1189–1246":"1189–1246","1194–1221":"1194–1221","1175–1245":"1175–1245","1221–1251":"1221–1251","1146–1198":"1146–1198","1165–1242":"1165–1242","about 1194":"umbes 1194","30 September 1198":"30. september 1198","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1165":"1165","1198":"1198","1175":"1175","1251":"1251","1194":"1194","1215":"1215","1246":"1246","1146":"1146","1245":"1245","1189":"1189","1221":"1221","about 1188":"umbes 1188","Broughton, Oxfordshire, England":"Broughton, Oxfordshire, England","Black Bourton, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Black Bourton, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Great Somerford, Wiltshire, England":"Great Somerford, Wiltshire, England","Somerford, Wiltshire, England, Great Britain":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1194–1221":"noin 1194–1221","1189–1246":"1189–1246","1194–1221":"1194–1221","1175–1245":"1175–1245","1221–1251":"1221–1251","1146–1198":"1146–1198","1165–1242":"1165–1242","about 1194":"noin 1194","30 September 1198":"30. syyskuuta 1198","1220":"1220","1242":"1242","1165":"1165","1198":"1198","1175":"1175","1251":"1251","1194":"1194","1215":"1215","1246":"1246","1146":"1146","1245":"1245","1189":"1189","1221":"1221","about 1188":"noin 1188","Broughton, Oxfordshire, England":"Broughton, Oxfordshire, England","Black Bourton, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Black Bourton, Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Great Somerford, Wiltshire, England":"Great Somerford, Wiltshire, England","Somerford, Wiltshire, England, Great Britain":"Wiltshire, En